        </task>
    </activity>
    <figure xml:id="fig-positive-enlargement">
        <caption>Positive Enlargement of a Triangle</caption>
        <interactive xml:id="enlargement" platform="jsxgraph" aspect="4:3" source="jsxgraph/positive_enlargement.js" width="100%">
            <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-enlargement" surface="jsxboard" aspect="4:3" />
            <instructions xml:id="enlargement-instructions">
                <p>Use the scale factor slider at the top to vary the scale factor from <m>0</m> to <m>4</m>. Observe how the enlarged triangle changes size relative to the original. You can also click and drag the center of enlargement (point <m>O</m>) or any of the vertices on the original triangle (<m>A</m>, <m>B</m>, and <m>C</m>) to explore how the transformation responds.</p>
            </instructions>
        </interactive>
    </figure>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formalise the definition and properties of enlargement.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Key Takeaways</title>
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Definition:</alert> The process of obtaining <m>\triangle A'B'C'</m> from <m>\triangle ABC</m> is called <term>enlargement</term>. <m>\triangle ABC</m> is the <term>object</term> and <m>\triangle A'B'C'</m> is the <term>image</term>. The point <m>O</m> is the <term>centre of enlargement</term>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Scale Factor:</alert> <m>\text{Scale Factor} = \frac{OA'}{OA} = \frac{OB'}{OB} = \frac{OC'}{OC} = \frac{A'B'}{AB}</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Properties:</alert> If <m>\text{SF} \gt 1</m>, the image is larger. If <m>0 \lt \text{SF} \lt 1</m>, the image is smaller (a reduction). Object and image remain similar.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <alert>Coordinate Rule:</alert> For an enlargement centred at the origin with scale factor <m>k</m>, the image of <m>(x,y)</m> is <m>(kx, ky)</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p xml:id="auto_31a385z2">
            <ul xml:id="auto_4eg4c10f">
                <li xml:id="auto_4dsdlfca">
                    <p xml:id="auto_n58s9906">
                    The process of obtaining triangle <m>A'B'C'</m> from triangle <m>ABC</m> is known as <m>\textbf{enlargement.}</m>
                    </p>
                </li>

                <li xml:id="auto_2lnsmva2">
                    <p xml:id="auto_98g16zv7">
                        Triangle <m>ABC</m> is said to be object and triangle <m>A'B'C'</m>, its image under enlargement.The point <m>O</m> is known as the <m>\textbf{centre of enlargement.}</m>
                    </p>

                </li>

                <li xml:id="auto_vtgvt40l">
                    <p xml:id="auto_g05680wi">
                        To determine the scale factor, divide the length of the enlarged image by the corresponding length of the original object.
                    </p>
                </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_5er8tzy0">
                                <me>
                                    \frac{OA'}{OA} = \frac{OB'}{OB} = \frac{OC'}{OC} 
                                </me>
                                
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_uq06vo0i">
                                <me>
                                    \frac{A'B'}{AB} = \frac{A'C'}{AC} = \frac{B'C'}{BC} 
                                </me>
                            </p>

                        <p xml:id="auto_1ezcytef">
                            <ul xml:id="auto_rslrk26j">
                                <li xml:id="auto_4xwwqhph">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_3xhedf08">
                                    Enlargement is a transformation that increases the size of a shape. The shape is enlarged by a scale factor. The scale factor is used to multiply the length of each side of the shape to get the length of the corresponding side of the enlarged shape.
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li xml:id="auto_6824y93k">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_d9gfqmjd">
                                        In an enlargement, the object and its image remain similar. The linear scale factor of the enlargement determines the proportional transformation.
                                    </p>
                                </li>

                                <li xml:id="auto_1setus8j">
                                <p xml:id="auto_xjn4seel">
                                        Lines connecting object points to their corresponding image points intersect at the center of enlargement. 
                                        This property helps in determining the center of enlargement when both the object and its image are given.
                                </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
        
    </insight>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application / Elaborate</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To apply enlargement with positive scale factors to solve problems.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Guide learners through worked examples. Emphasize finding <m>OP'</m> before computing the scale factor. Use tables to organise coordinate calculations for multi-vertex shapes.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <example xml:id="auto_rmfu42uf">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_cb9vy2je">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_wl455vxd">
                In the figure below, Triangle <m>P'Q'R'</m> is  the enlarged image of triangle <m>PQR</m>, with center <m>O</m>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_0ts9te80">
                (a) Given that <m>OP=6</m> <m>cm</m> and <m>PP'=9</m> <m>cm</m>, determine the linear scale factor of the enlargement.
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_zvd18ufi">
                (b) If <m>QR=4</m> <m>cm</m>, find the length of <m>Q'R'</m>
            </p>

            <figure xml:id="Triangle1">
                <caption></caption>

            <image width="50%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="Triangle1">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (R) at (3,0);
                    \coordinate (Q) at (2.2,1.1);  
                    \coordinate (P) at (2.5,3);

                    \coordinate (R') at (6,0);
                    \coordinate (Q') at (4.4,2.2);  
                    \coordinate (P') at (5,6);

                    % Draw base triangles
                    \draw (O) -- (R);
                    \draw (O) -- (R');
                    \draw (R) -- (Q) -- (P) -- cycle;
                    \draw (R') -- (Q') -- (P') -- cycle;

                    % Draw ONE straight line passing through O, Q, and Q'
                    \draw (O) -- (Q) -- (Q');

                    % Draw straight line from O to P and P'
                    \draw (O) -- (P) -- (P');

                    % Shade the inner triangles with different colors
                    \fill[blue!50,opacity=0.6] (R) -- (Q) -- (P) -- cycle;  % Blue triangle
                    \fill[cyan!50,opacity=0.6] (R') -- (Q') -- (P') -- cycle; % Cyan triangle

                    % Label points
                    \node[above left] at (O) {O};
                    \node[below] at (R) {R};
                    \node[below] at (R') {R'};
                    \node[above] at (P) {P};
                    \node[above] at (P') {P'};
                    \node[left] at (Q) {Q};
                    \node[right] at (Q') {Q'};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                
            </image>
        </figure>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_q5s4onq3">
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text {(a). Linear scale factor is:} \amp </mrow>
                    <mrow> \frac {OP'}{OP} =\amp \frac{(6+9)}{6}</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{15}{6}</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac {5}{2}</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_o4s48c6b">
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text {(b).Linear scale factor } =\amp \frac {Q'R'}{QR}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\text {But QR}  =\amp 4\, cm </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text {Therefore,} \frac {Q'R'}{QR}= \amp \frac {5}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow>Q'P' =\amp \frac{(4 \times 5)}{2} </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp \frac{20}{2}</mrow>
                    <mrow> Q'P' = \amp 10\, cm</mrow>

                </md>
            </p>
            
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="auto_8vckl3z7">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_zxo9g61r">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_j8dvlo3l">
                Construct any triangle <m>XYZ</m> and choose a point <m>O</m> outside the triangle. Using <m>O</m> as the center of enlargement and a scale factor of <m>4</m>, construct the enlarged image of triangle <m>XYZ</m> under the enlargement.
            </p>

        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_3p2oe705">
                
            </p>
            <figure xml:id="Triangle3">
                <caption></caption>
            <image width="50%">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                <latex-image label="Triangle3">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        % Define coordinates
                        \coordinate (O) at (0,0);
                        \coordinate (Z) at (3,0);
                        \coordinate (Y) at (2.2,1.1);  
                        \coordinate (X) at (2.5,3);

                        \coordinate (Z') at (6,0);
                        \coordinate (Y') at (4.4,2.2);  
                        \coordinate (X') at (5,6);

                        % Draw base triangles
                        \draw (O) -- (Z);
                        \draw (O) -- (Z');
                        \draw (Z) -- (Y) -- (X) -- cycle;
                        \draw (Z') -- (Y') -- (X') -- cycle;

                        % Draw ONE straight line passing through O, Y, and Y'
                        \draw (O) -- (Y) -- (Y');

                        % Draw straight line from O to X and X'
                        \draw (O) -- (X) -- (X');

                        % Shade the inner triangles with different colors
                        \fill[yellow!60,opacity=0.6] (Z) -- (Y) -- (X) -- cycle;  % Yellow triangle
                        \fill[orange!60,opacity=0.6] (Z') -- (Y') -- (X') -- cycle; % Orange triangle

                        % Draw right angle signs inside triangles at Y and Y'
                        \draw (Y) ++(0.2,0) -- ++(0,0.2) -- ++(-0.2,0);
                        \draw (Y') ++(0.2,0) -- ++(0,0.2) -- ++(-0.2,0);

                        % Label points
                        \node[above left] at (O) {O};
                        \node[below] at (Z) {Z};
                        \node[below] at (Z') {Z'};
                        \node[above] at (X) {X};
                        \node[above] at (X') {X'};
                        \node[left] at (Y) {Y};
                        \node[right] at (Y') {Y'};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                
            </image>

            </figure>

            <p xml:id="auto_9pmyrfhh">
                By measurement;
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_dmxscojn">
                <m>OX=1.8</m> <m>cm</m>, <m>OY=3.2</m> <m>cm</m> and <m>OZ=2.7</m> <m>cm</m>.
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_x5jq5rie">
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{To determine X', the image of X, We follow these steps:} \amp </mrow>
                    <mrow>OX= \amp 1.8\, cm</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac {OX'}{OX}= \amp \text{scale factor}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{OX'}{1.8} =4\amp </mrow>
                    <mrow>OX'= \amp 4 \times 1.8\, cm</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 7.2\, cm</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_0q3makca">
                Extend <m>OX</m> and measure <m>7.2</m> <m>cm</m> from <m>O</m> to get <m>X'</m>.
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_x99f7ld4">
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{To determine Y', the image of Y, We follow these steps:} \amp </mrow>
                     <mrow>OY= \amp 3.2\, cm</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac {OY'}{OY}= \amp \text{scale factor}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{OY'}{3.2} =4\amp </mrow>
                    <mrow>OX'= \amp 4 \times 3.2\, cm</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 12.8\, cm</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_dhs15ac5">
                Extend <m>OY</m> and measure <m>12.8</m> <m>cm</m> from <m>O</m> to get <m>Y'</m>.
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_fnjiy2dv">
                <md>
                    <mrow>\text{To determine Z', the image of Z, We follow these steps:} \amp </mrow>
                     <mrow>OZ= \amp 2.7\, cm</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac {OZ'}{OZ}= \amp \text{scale factor}</mrow>
                    <mrow>\frac{OZ'}{2.7} =4\amp </mrow>
                    <mrow>OX'= \amp 4 \times 2.7\, cm</mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 10.8\, cm</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_jof32lb1">
                Extend <m>OZ</m> and measure <m>10.8</m> <m>cm</m> from <m>O</m> to get <m>Z'</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="auto_nbwh8vap">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_ofd42070">
                
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_xsv4mfnm">
                Triangle <m>A'B'C'</m>  is the image of triangle <m>ABC</m> under an enlargement.Locate the centre of the enlargement.
            </p>
            <image source="graph-paper6.png">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
            </image>

        </statement>
        
        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_s1ardsum">
                To locate the centre of enlargement we follow the following steps:
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_vq1rgy2l">
                Draw lines connecting point <m>A</m> to <m>A'</m>,  <m>B</m> to <m>B'</m> and <m>C</m> to <m>C'</m> and extend those lines. The intersection point of those lines, will be the center of enlargement.
            </p>
            <image source="graph-paper5.png">
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
            </image>

        </solution>
    </example>

    <example xml:id="auto_ll03uhrf">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_za297ey0">
                Given that <m>A\, (6,8)</m>, <m>B\, (8,8)</m>, <m>C\, (12,8)</m>, <m>D\, (14,2)</m> and <m>E\, (10,0)</m> are the Vertices of the pentagon, find the vertices of its image after an enlargement with origin as the centre and scale factor of:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a)" cols="2">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>2</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_zgtukr20">
                Given the centre of enlargement is <m>(0,0)</m> and the scale factor <m>k</m>,We find the coordinates of the image as follows;
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_pnx0bgqr">
                <m>(x',y')=</m> <m>(kx,ky)</m>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_lxh1qk4q">
                Applying this to the given co-odinates we get;
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_hybv2qwr">
                (a) for a scale factor of <m>2</m>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_bh3s7vw8">
                <md>
                    <mrow> A'=\amp(2\times 6), (2 \times 8)=(12,16) </mrow>
                     <mrow> B'=\amp(2\times 8), (2 \times 8)=(16,16) </mrow>
                      <mrow> C'=\amp(2\times 12), (2 \times 2)=(24,16) </mrow>
                       <mrow> D'=\amp(2\times 14), (2 \times 8)=(28,4) </mrow>
                        <mrow> E'=\amp(2\times 10), (2 \times 0)=(20,0) </mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{Vertices of the image}= \amp A' (12,16), B'(16,16), C' (24,16), D' (28,4) \text{and} E' (20,0)</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_kjk55cc4">
                (b) for a scale factor of <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>
            </p>

            <p xml:id="auto_hdu074qh">
                <md>
                    <mrow> A'=\amp(\frac{1}{2}\times 6), (\frac{1}{2} \times 8)=(3,4) </mrow>
                     <mrow> B'=\amp(\frac{1}{2}\times 8), (\frac{1}{2} \times 8)=(4,4) </mrow>
                      <mrow> C'=\amp(\frac{1}{2}\times 12), (\frac{1}{2} \times 2)=(6,4) </mrow>
                       <mrow> D'=\amp(\frac{1}{2}\times 14), (\frac{1}{2} \times 8)=(7,1) </mrow>
                        <mrow> E'=\amp(\frac{1}{2}\times 10), (\frac{1}{2} \times 0)=(5,0) </mrow>
                        <mrow>\text{vertices of the image}= \amp A' (3,4), B'(4,4), C' (6,4), D' (7,1) \text{and} E' (5,O)</mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment / Evaluate</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    5 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formatively assess individual learner understanding.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    Learners independently complete a short assessment task (select from the exercises below).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge learner understanding and identify any common misconceptions that need to be addressed in the next lesson.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Answer Key</title>
            <p>
                <alert>Q1.</alert> <m>P(1,2)</m>, <m>Q(3,2)</m>, <m>R(2,5)</m>. Scale factor <m>3</m>, centre origin.
                <m>P'=(3,6)</m>, <m>Q'=(9,6)</m>, <m>R'=(6,15)</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Q2.</alert> <m>OX=4</m>, <m>OX'=12</m>. Scale factor <m>= \frac{12}{4} = 3</m>. <m>YZ=5</m>, so <m>Y'Z' = 5 \times 3 = 15</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Q3.</alert> Rectangle <m>A(2,1)</m>, <m>B(6,1)</m>, <m>C(6,3)</m>, <m>D(2,3)</m>. Scale factor <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>, centre origin.
                <m>A'=(1, 0.5)</m>, <m>B'=(3, 0.5)</m>, <m>C'=(3, 1.5)</m>, <m>D'=(1, 1.5)</m>.
                Original dimensions: <m>4 \times 2</m>. Image dimensions: <m>2 \times 1</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                <alert>Q4.</alert> Construction steps for scale factor <m>4</m> with external centre <m>O</m>:
                <ol>
                    <li><p>Draw the object triangle and mark the external centre <m>O</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Draw rays from <m>O</m> through each vertex of the object.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Measure the distance from <m>O</m> to each vertex and multiply by <m>4</m>.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Mark the image vertices along each ray at the calculated distances.</p></li>
                    <li><p>Connect the image vertices to form the enlarged triangle.</p></li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

